I love instant gratification, so I'm always misting and removing markings on my quilts as I go. 

My favorite way to remove the blue Mark B Gone marker. Mix 1c water, 1tsp baking soda in a misting spray bottle, mist as you go. 

A few tips..
🧡Make sure to not remove markings where you haven't quilted yet. 
🧡Do not apply any heat until you know those markings are 100% gone. 
🧡Generally, after I've completed quilting a quilt I'll mist the entire quilt again. Let it dry and then repeat until the markings are gone. 
🧡If you're worried about fabrics bleeding, wash first. 

Happy hump day! 
Natalia

This question might be one of the most common questions I get, and I'm more than happy to answer. 

I've been hand-guided quilting on @gammillquilting machines for almost 16 years and have nothing but praises to sing. 

Fun fact. My first machine was an 18" Gammill on a 10' table. Before purchasing that machine, although  I had others do machine quilting for me, I had never even seen a longarm machine in person. But, I had done my research, and I knew that Gammill machines were well built and I'd be getting my money's worth. 

I purchased that machine, and still never touched a longarm machine until it was delivered and setup in my home. 

I tell you this because you can do it. I literally had no idea what a longarm machine really was, but I was determined to learn everything I could, by teaching myself, through a ton of trial and error. I had so many sleepless nights in the beginning, I was also 8 months pregnant. 🤔

Every single day, I would just load fabric on the machine and practice, practice and practice more. The more I practiced the more comfortable and confident I became.

Now, almost 16 years later I've upgraded to a 22" machine on a 10' table. I do have the Statler Stitcher on my machine, however, I love hand-guided quilting so much that generally I'm just using my Statler for edge to edge type quilting.

Happy Wednesday friends!

While working through my new class Visual Guide to Machine Quilting Quilt Blocks, of course there were quite a few video "outtakes" and bloopers. Lots of those videos never get shared, but for some reason I just couldn't delete this one. 

All the time I'm asked if I really quilt with just one hand, and what does my machine look like? 

I thought this clip was the perfect clip to share both. Yes, I do really always quilt with just one hand, I talked a bit about this in one of the Visual Guide to Machine Quilting Quilt Blocks Live follow up videos, it's the way I learned to quilt, and it's just what worked best for me. 😁

I do all of my quilting on a Gammill 22" machine on a 10' table. I most often stitch in stitch regulated mode with my stitch length set at 12-15spi.

The ruler I'm using is the 4n1 with our Piece N Quilt Pop Socket Ruler Grip.
